article.headline: Duncan, Ginobili post double-doubles
article.linkText: Work cut out for Skiles: Bulls lose 7th straight
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Tim Duncan and the San Antonio Spurs outlasted the surprisingly competitive Chicago Bulls. Duncan scored 13 of his 16 points in the second half and had 10 rebounds in the defending NBA champion Spurs' 109-98 victory over the Bulls on Wednesday night. Manu Ginobili led the Spurs with 17 points and 11 rebounds, Tony Parker added 15 points and Ron Mercer had 12. Eddy Curry and Lonny Baxter had 19 points each for Chicago, which lost its second straight game under interim coach Pete Myers. The Bulls, who have lost seven straight overall, are expected to hire former Phoenix coach Scott Skiles to replace Bill Cartwright, fired Monday. "I'm grateful for the opportunity. It was a fun couple of days until Scott gets here," Myers said. "I was satisfied with a lot of things we did out there. Our guys competed well, particularly at the end of the game. I felt like there was a renewed spirit out there on the floor." Spurs coach Gregg Popovich praised the Bulls. "The Bulls did a good job," Popovich said. "They're playing hard even though things haven't gone their way. ... You have to give them credit for the way they played. I'm concerned that they scored 98 points. We can't beat people when they put up those kinds of numbers. That's not who we are." Chicago used a 17-8 run, capped by Donyell Marshall's 3-pointer, to pull to 83-80 with 6:27 to play, but San Antonio answered with a 16-4 run to make it 99-84. Chicago could get no closer than 10 points the rest of the way. "Any time a team has been through as much as we have you get to a point where you just say, `Hey, let's just go out there and play," Chicago's Jalen Rose. San Antonio, which won its second straight and fourth in the last five games, scored on seven of its first eight possessions in the third quarter and led 61-49 on Duncan's jump shot with 8:09 to play in the period. "It was a close game early on and we had to do something to change that," Parker said. "We had to be aggressive. I think we didn't came out defensively like we should have to start the game."

Game notes
The win was San Antonio's fifth straight over Chicago. ... Duncan has 11 double-doubles this season and 356 in his career. ... Chicago's Jalen Rose appeared in his 253rd consecutive game, the fourth longest active steak in the NBA. ... Scottie Pippen (left corneal abrasion) and Tyson Chandler (sore lower back) both sat out the game for the Bulls.
